column162: in a scary and disturbing way. He is the first serious national candidate in our or any other major democracy to sp...ell out the battle lines that people on a grassroots level have woken up to -- the battle is between what is left of nation-states that are democracies
column163: in which people have some say over their national policies and can pay attention to national values and priorities -- versus the global collective script of what is emerging clearly as an internationally globalized set agenda
column164: passed in bills such as TPP
column166: Congresses and Parliaments. This fear about actually what is actually bad and scary about globalization and citizen decision-making is what led to British voters choosing Brexit. I am not taking sides in any of these discussions but noting that you don't have to be an idiot or a racist to see the value of a nation-state with its own citizens' local or national agenda
column167: against the agendas of globalized special interests who increasingly want to transcend parliaments and congresses.  Trump is not wrong to spell out this critique -- it is the center of history right now in the West -- and I for one am worried about the loss of the nation-state - - about what is now obvious as being the clearly planned erosion of the powers of democracies in nation-states
column168: in the face of a globalization agenda by special interests.  Much more disturbing to me than this legitimate critique
column169: is his hyping of the terror threat -- and his manipulation of some terrible recent news events to use fear to boost his mandate. America is far more safe and stable than the 24 hour news cycle proposes; and crime is tragic
column170: but it should not be used to hijack listeners' neocortical responses. As far as his even mentioning the poor
column171: well that is a welcome addition to political discussion -- democrats would do well to match that concern as very few people left in the US any longer feel even middle class. A skillful if in some ways troubling performance. column10: 2008 ¬∑ A B.Middleton first: 2 Notes in 1 weekWhassup family
column11: Just another interesting couple of paragraphs that I came across yesterday:*************************************************************Email To Hillary In her self-aggrandizing non-concession speech Tuesday night
column12: Sen. Hillary Clinton invited voters to log on to www.HillaryClinton.com and tell her what we think she should do now. We...ll
column13: I dropped Hillary an e-mail and
column15: I'd like to share it with you. My letter went like this: Dear Sen. Clinton
column16: I was offended by your self-centered
column17: combative speech after yesterday's Minnesota and South Dakota primaries. Your refusal to concede the race
column18: to acknowledge Sen. Obama's historic win and to extend common courtesy to Sen. Obama make your statements about Democratic Party unity seem phony. You lost the election yesterday
column19: but rather than step aside graciously
column21: condescended the winner and tried to make the night all about you. Your stubborn arrogance was apparent before you took the stage. Even though it was at least half-an-hour after Sen. Obama sewed up the winning number of delegates
column22: you allowed Terry McAuliffe to introduce you as "the next president of the United States!" Shameful. Later
column23: you told your supporters that you were not going to make a decision. But there is nothing for you to decide
column24: because Sen. Obama won the nomination fair and square. The electoral process has made the decision for you. Whether you're prepared to acknowledge it or not
column25: the campaign is over and Sen. Obama is our party's nominee.You can be justifiably proud of the more than 17 million voters who cast ballots for you during the primaries. But when you imply that these voters could become "invisible
column26: you are being inaccurate and divisive. Even more divisive was your reference to count(ing) every vote" (sour grapes over the outcome of the Rules and Bylaws Committee meeting) and your smiling silence as your supporters chanted
column27: "Denver! Denver!" These are not examples of a commitment to party unity. They are selfish
column28: stiff-necked grandstanding.You played up the significance of your running for President as a woman but ignored the greatness Sen. Obama winning the nomination as a black candidate. You went out of your way to mention the 90-year-old ladies who remember when women could not vote and the parents who pointed to you as an example to their daughters. But what about blacks who lived under Jim Crow and remember what it was like when black folks couldn't vote? What about us black parents who point with pride to Obama as an example to our children? We weren't important enough to merit a mention in your speech. By ignoring the monumental racial importance of Tuesday night
column30: black America at large and the heroes of all races who fought
column31: suffered and died for racial equality from slavery up through the present day. Your disdain for Sen. Obama was clear in your patronizing statement
column32: "I would like all of us to take a moment to recognize him and his supporters for all they have accomplished." Gee
column33: thanks. Here we are at one of the most significant social and political milestones in American history and you treat it like a footnote. Sen. Obama has literally changed our nation but the only thing you gave him credit for was running "an extraordinary race" and inspiring and empowering voters to get involved in the process. Contrast your dismissive acknowledgment with Obama's glowing praise for your history-making campaign and it's easy to see that his character is made of much greater stuff than yours. And you wonder why black folks cheered when Father Michael Pfleger mocked you. As a final insult on Tuesday night
column34: you didn't even phone Sen. Obama to congratulate him on securing the nomination. Instead
column35: you waited for him to call you and then allowed his call to go to voicemail. Twice. You finally got around to returning Obama's calls an hour after he'd left his messages. That was rank arrogance
column37: bad sportsmanship and the opposite of party unity.Our party and our nation deserve better. Sincerely

column49: 2006 ¬∑ Spike Lee's Katrina MasterpieceFor those of you who have on demand cable (legal or bootlegged)
column50: let me strongly recommend that you take a look at Spike's latest documentary on the current state of New Orleans.  As an average college student
column51: I didn't stay up on things down there like many other people did but I found the state of that area to be still ABSOLUTELY apalling . . . 3...65 days later.  So even if you don't have money to contribute
column52: give of your time and educate yourself on what's really goin on this country.  I have never felt and still don't feel ashamed to be an American but some of what I saw has furthered my distrust and disbelief of a lot of our leaders here in the States.  Take a look at this documentary when you get a chance and post your comments.  Peace.More things that make you go HMMMM . . . See More1 CommentShareBrandon MiddletonSeptember 23
